This paper discusses a new field-normalized indicator for citation impact, which is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The paper draws on early insights in bibliometrics and focuses on the normalization of citation counts across different fields. The paper does not discuss any specific computer science applications or technologies, but its methodology and findings are relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), cybersecurity (cs.CY), social networks (cs.SI), and cryptography (cs.CR).
